<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05016d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05016d">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05016d"> 16(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Kapporeth = mercy-seat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Now what was the <mark>mercy seat</mark>? It was simply the lid of the box. The Hebrew <mark><i>Kapporeth</i></mark> means to cover, and the holy of holies is called the house of the Kapporeth. <br>Here then the whole case lies in a nutshell. If Jehovah and God the Father are indeed the same, we may say to the Christians&mdash;your God was once carried about in a box, and used to get out and sit on the cover. <small> G.W. Foote, <a name="BROM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BROM"><cite title="source">Bible Romances</cite></a>, 4th ed. (1922) [A God in a Box] 119</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Exod. 25:17: <i>And thou shalt make a mercy seat of pure gold &hellip; And thou shalt put the mercy seat above the ark</i> </mm> </dd></dl>
